[{"id":29860,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> (Solid)","U.V. Light","Visualisation agent as a component of mobile phase","Spraying of an appropriate reagent"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Thin Layer Chromatography is a technique used to isolate non-volatile mixtures. The experiment is conducted on a sheet of aluminium foil, plastic, or glass which is coated with a thin layer of adsorbent material. The material usually used is aluminium oxide, cellulose, or silica gel.</p><p>The sample spots can be observed under a UV light chamber,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;solid or by spraying of an appropriate reagent which can react with the sample spot.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30077,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["isomeric compounds","chiral compounds","meso compounds","optical isomers"],"answer":3,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":30036,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{RCO} \\overline{\\mathrm{O}} < \\mathrm{HC}=\\overline{\\mathrm{C}} < \\overline{\\mathrm{R}} < \\overline{\\mathrm{N}} \\mathrm{H}_2$","$\\overline{\\mathrm{R}} < \\mathrm{HC} \\equiv \\overline{\\mathrm{C}} < \\mathrm{RCO} \\overline{\\mathrm{O}} < \\overline{\\mathrm{N}} \\mathrm{H}_2$","$\\mathrm{RCO} \\overline{\\mathrm{O}} < \\overline{\\mathrm{N}} \\mathrm{H}_2 < \\mathrm{HC} \\equiv \\overline{\\mathrm{C}} < \\overline{\\mathrm{R}}$","$\\mathrm{RCO} \\overline{\\mathrm{O}} < \\mathrm{HC} \\equiv \\overline{\\mathrm{C}} < \\overline{\\mathrm{N}} \\mathrm{H}_2 < \\overline{\\mathrm{R}}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Correct order of increasing basic strength is\n$$\n\\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{COO}^{(-)} < \\mathrm{CH} \\equiv \\mathrm{C}^{(-)} < \\mathrm{NH}_2^{(-)} < \\mathrm{R}^{(-)}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":29977,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><mi>B</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>C</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>D</mi></math>","<math><mi>D</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>C</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>B</mi></math>","<math><mi>B</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>C</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>D</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>A</mi></math>","<math><mi>C</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>B</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>D</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>pKa</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>logKa</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ka</mi><mo>&#8593;</mo><mi>pKa</mi><mo>&#8595;</mo></math>&nbsp;&amp; vice versa<br /><br />Acidic character&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>Ka</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>pKa</mi></mfrac></math><br /><br />Acidic character &alpha; stability of anion (Conjugate base)<br /><br />Conjugate base are<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/523d7d29-df5c-4473-a27b-2cc486a53cb7-image.png\" style=\"width: 457px; height: 272px;\" /><br /><br />Stability of conjugate base&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>or</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>or</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>&nbsp;is more dominating than&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mrow><mo>(</mo> <mi>B</mi> <mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> </math>&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;at para so exerts&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp; &amp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>&nbsp;<mi>&gt;<mi>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math><br /><br />So it is highly stable anion in<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mrow><mo>(</mo> <mi>C</mi> <mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> </math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;at meta exerts only&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;effect<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mrow><mo>(</mo> <mi>A</mi> <mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> </math>&nbsp;No <math><msup><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;withdrawing or electron releasing group.<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mrow><mo>(</mo> <mi>D</mi> <mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> </math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>OCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;has&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mo>&#38;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;but&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>&nbsp;dominates<br /><br />So acidic strength will be<br /><br /><math><mi>B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi>D</mi></math> </mi></mi><br /><br />Therefore <math> <mrow> <mi>p</mi><mi>K</mi><mi>a</mi> </mrow> </math> values will be in the order<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mi>B</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>C</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>D</mi> </mrow> </math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29879,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>&nbsp;Electrophilic centre are areas of low electron density. Most often they are atoms which contain a full of partial positive charge. In the given structure the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>CN</mi></math> group, the Keto group &amp; the double bond in conjugation with Keto group are the&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> electrophilic centres.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2454e9d3-8009-4877-883b-38a3a1549038-image.png\" style=\"width: 217px; height: 186px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29858,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>An asymmetric carbon atom is a carbon atom that is attached to four different types of atoms or groups of atoms.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/90aaba62-174a-4ad9-a0d7-8265b5f14ec2-image.png\" style=\"width: 298px; height: 110px;\" /></p><p>Number of compounds containing asymmetric carbons are three.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29994,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/123456aaaaaaa.PNG\" style=\"width: 52px; height: 61px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/234567.PNG\" style=\"width: 60px; height: 59px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/345678acsfadfad.PNG\" style=\"width: 106px; height: 68px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/456789.PNG\" style=\"width: 64px; height: 59px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"In A,B,D entire ring involved in delocalisation and follow&nbsp;huckel rule of (4n+2)pi electrons. so, they are aromatic and are more stable.<br />While in C one carbon is&nbsp;sp<sup>3</sup>&nbsp;so&nbsp;non planar. so, non aromatic and it is&nbsp;less stable.<br />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (02 Apr)","image":null},{"id":29814,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-Methyl-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>-oxohexanoic acid","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-Formyl-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>-methylhexan-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math>-oic acid","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>-Methyl-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-oxohexan-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math>-oic acid","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>-Formyl-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-methylhexanoic acid"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>IUPAC name of the following compound is<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/44437ce8-ff8d-4677-b034-12d505b05b2a-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 168px;\" /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-Methyl-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>-oxo-hexanoic acid</p><ol>\t<li>\t<p>Identify the longest continuous carbon chain that contains the carboxyl group (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>COOH</mi></math>). In this case, it is a six-carbon chain.</p>\t</li>\t<li>\t<p>Number the carbon chain starting from the end closest to the carboxyl group. The carboxyl carbon is assigned the number <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>.</p>\t</li>\t<li>\t<p>Identify and name any substituents attached to the carbon chain. In this case, there is a methyl group attached to the second carbon atom of the chain.</p>\t</li>\t<li>\t<p>Combine the substituent name with the parent chain name, with a hyphen in between. The resulting name is &quot;2-methylhexanoic acid&quot;.</p>\t</li>\t<li>\t<p>Finally, add the prefix &quot;oxo&quot; to indicate the presence of a ketone group (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>) on the fifth carbon of the chain.</p>\t</li></ol></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29863,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The estimation of halogens in organic compounds is usually done by carius method.</p><p>Percentage of Bromine&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>Atomic</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Br</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>Molecular</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>AgBr</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>Mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>AgBr</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>Mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>the</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>organic</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>compound</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>80</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>188</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>34</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29831,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["2-Bromo-1-deuterobutane","2-Bromo-2-deuterobutane","2-Bromo-3-deuterobutane","2-Bromo-1-deutero-2-methylpropane"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The isomeric deuterated bromide with molecular formula&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><mi>DBr</mi></math>&nbsp;having two chiral carbon atoms is&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1e465efd-26a9-46a9-8909-39ab102620ff-9894607.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 210px;\" /></p><p>2-Bromo-3-deuterobutane</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29848,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Steam distillation","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>ft</mi></math> long column of silica gel","Sublimation","Preparative TLC (Thin Layer Chromatography)"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/acb15856-5763-459b-84d4-d44d68f02551-image.png\" style=\"width: 317px; height: 300px;\" /></p><p>Solvent polarity has been related to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub></math> value of nitrocompounds.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn><mi>mg</mi></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math>-nitrophenol and picric acid have different <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub></math> value on silica gel plate</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math>&nbsp;Preparative TLC is best to separate <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn><mi>mg</mi></math> of para nitrophenol and picric acid</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29797,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Reactivity of aromatic compounds towards electrophilic substitution depends on the electron density on benzene ring. Higher the electron density on benzene ring, more be the reactivity towards electrophilic substitution reaction. Hence, the correct decreasing order is</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cd6d6f0c-c7e0-4b6b-9fe2-be78cf9aefdf.png\" style=\"width: 475px; height: 194px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29985,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["(A)-(r),(B)-(s), (C)-(p),(D)-(q)","(A)-(p),(B)-(s), (C)-(r),(D)-(q)","(A)-(r), (B)-(p), (C)-(q), (D)-(s)","(A)-(r),(B)-(p), (C)-(s),(D)-(q)"],"answer":2,"solution":"(a) Charcoal treatment removes coloured impurity through adsorption.\n(b) Steam distillation separates the mixture of $o$-nitrophenol and $p$-nitrophenol. The $o$-nitrophenol is steam volatile (due to intramolecular hydrogen bonding), and the para isomer is not volatile.\n(c) Fractional distillation separates crude naphtha. Naphtha is a flammable liquid hydrocarbon mixture.\n(d) Distillation under reduced pressure separates mixture of glycerol and sugars. Vacuum distillation lowers the boiling point and prevents decomposition.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":29976,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Bromo<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>methylpent<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>ene","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Bromo<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>methyl<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>dimethylprop<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>ene","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Bromo<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>methyl pent<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>ene","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Bromo<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>dimethylbut<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>ene"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img height=\"200\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e2b1964c-4981-447e-bdbc-485ce3489a47-image.png\" width=\"269\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29773,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Given, an organic compound moved by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>Solvent moved by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>The R<sub>f</sub> (retardation factor) value is the ratio of the solute’s distance travelled to the solvent’s distance travelled.</p><p>Retardation factor <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>Distance</mi><mo> </mo><mi>travelled</mi><mo> </mo><mi>by</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>sample</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>organic</mi><mo> </mo><mi>compound</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable><mrow><mi>Distance</mi><mo> </mo><mi>travelled</mi><mo> </mo><mi>by</mi><mo> </mo><mi>solvent</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>By putting the values in the above formula,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29922,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Aromatic compounds are considered as the compound which contains a conjugated planar ring system with delocalized pi-electrons cloud located at alternate double bond and single bond. For a compound to be aromatic it should follow Huckel&rsquo;s rule which says that the compound should satisfy&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></math>&nbsp;electrons.</p><p>For Aromaticity, full conjugation of&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></math>&nbsp;electrons&nbsp;should be there in closed ring.</p><p>(A) Non-Aromatic</p><p>(B) Aromatic</p><p>(C) Aromatic</p><p>(D) Anti-Aromatic</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29900,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/00acac01-6b66-48c8-be81-4dc40b48eda3-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 131px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e458fad7-ab24-49f0-aa84-844d3dd51657-image.png\" style=\"width: 140px; height: 121px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1d52a8c8-0258-460b-8f1d-b17c7225c755-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 126px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f8794543-16ef-4b87-8028-1f83310fc53e-image.png\" style=\"width: 532px; height: 203px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29717,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["(I) \\( > \\) (II) \\( > \\) (III)","(I) \\( > \\) (III) \\( > \\) (II)","\\(\\text { (II) } > \\text { (I) } > \\text { (III) }\\)","\\(\\text { (III) } > \\text { (II) } > \\text { (I) }\\)"],"answer":0,"solution":"(1) Neutral structures are more stable than charged ones. Therefore I is more stable than II and III.\n(2) +ve charge on less electronegative atom is more stable i.e., $\\mathrm{C}^{\\oplus}$ is more stable than $\\mathrm{O}^{\\oplus}$ Order is I $>$ III $>$ III","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30035,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$59.0$","$47.4$","$23.7$","$29.5$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Moles of $\\mathrm{HCl}$ reacting with ammonia\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& =(\\text { moles of } \\mathrm{HCl} \\text { absorbed })-(\\text { moles of } \\mathrm{NaOH} \\text { solution required) } \\\\\n& =\\left(20 \\times 0.1 \\times 10^{-3}\\right)-\\left(15 \\times 0.1 \\times 10^{-3}\\right) \\\\\n& =\\text { moles of } \\mathrm{NH}_3 \\text { evolved. } \\\\\n& =\\text { moles of nitrogen in organic compound }\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\therefore \\text { wt. of nitrogen in org. comp }=0.5 \\times 10^{-3} \\times 14 \\\\\n& =7 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{~g} \\\\\n& \\% w t=\\frac{7 \\times 10^{-3}}{29.5 \\times 10^{-3}}=23.7 \\% \\\\\n&\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":29738,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{f}} \\text { of } \\mathrm{A}=\\frac{5}{12.5} \\quad \\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{f}} \\text { of } \\mathrm{C}=\\frac{10}{12.5} \\\\ & \\text { Ratio }=\\frac{\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{f}(\\mathrm{A})}}{\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{f}(\\mathrm{C})}}=\\frac{1}{2}=0.5 \\text { or } 50 \\times 10^{-2}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30062,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{Cl}$","$\\mathrm{OCOCH}_3$","$\\mathrm{OC}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5$","$\\mathrm{NH}_2$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Rate of reaction will be fastest when $\\mathrm{Z}$ is $\\mathrm{Cl}$ because it is a weakest base","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":29705,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false"],"answer":3,"solution":"The elements present in the compound are converted from covalent form into ionic form by fusing the compound with sodium in Lassigne's test","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29651,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["B & D only","A, C & D only","B, D & E only","A, D & E only"],"answer":0,"solution":"Evaluating each statement:<br><b>(A)</b> TRUE - More covalent bonds with lesser charge separation increases resonance stabilization.<br><b>(B)</b> FALSE - In electromeric effect, unsaturated systems show +E effect toward nucleophiles and -E effect toward electrophiles, opposite to stated.<br><b>(C)</b> TRUE - Inductive effect of polar groups affects melting points, boiling points, and dipole moments.<br><b>(D)</b> FALSE - Greater alkyl substitution on doubly bonded carbons decreases heat of hydrogenation (more substituted alkenes are more stable).<br><b>(E)</b> TRUE - Higher s-character of orbital holding negative charge increases carbanion stability.<br><br>Statements NOT true: B and D. Therefore answer is B & D only.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29737,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["(A)-(II), (B)-(I), (C)-(IV), (D)-(III)","(A)-(III), (B)-(I), (C)-(II), (D)-(IV)","(A)-(I), (B)-(III), (C)-(IV), (D)-(II)","(A)-(III), (B)-(I), (C)-(IV), (D)-(II)"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/yYu-RzwLfentMRasMMSGWloVP-zXlXtQWdZbulG84ow.original.fullsize.png\"><br> $\\qquad$ $\\Rightarrow$ Position isomers<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9PI_c_15H_Q2qmVFXbaOzf6kSxrkyJKaDtIwthtE2eI.original.fullsize.png\"><br> $\\qquad$ $\\Rightarrow$ Metamers<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EhLSR1ceWgwv1Br8isbI4XaINmPCr1wKTspSuWMKeSA.original.fullsize.png\"><br> $\\qquad$ $\\Rightarrow$ Functional isomers<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5U5Rk697gnGmkwORJFdJvFXhiLRe4b-e24YwrEK8J7g.original.fullsize.png\"><br> $\\qquad$ $\\Rightarrow$ Chain isomers","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29727,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Four","Two","One","Three"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Q060Y9NTtOvog1E0NH7WmY4XsecTN5BrWrtCuaSMUNM.original.fullsize.png\"><br />only one $2^{\\circ}$ carbon is present in this compound.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29866,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9b43910e-5d70-4353-9e2c-29a3eedbdb1e-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 141px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f32b4831-c808-4499-8fa9-afbc32a92891-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 148px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9977bd4f-afde-4694-bdf5-d8e1de14520d-image.png\" style=\"width: 140px; height: 154px;\" /></p>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/539cb0f8-ca25-4fe6-8675-1f16cb85d87e-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 151px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bc387d24-2196-4bc4-80f8-5c2748d9c40e-image.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 305px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29943,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Fractional distillation","Differential distillation","Steam distillation","Distillation under reduced pressure"],"answer":3,"solution":"Glycerol can be separated from spent-lye in soap industry by using Reduce pressure Distillation Technique.&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (03 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30019,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math> <mrow> <mtext>III</mtext> <mo>&#62;</mo> <mtext>I</mtext> <mo>&#62;</mo> <mtext>II</mtext> <mo>&#62;</mo> <mtext>IV</mtext> </mrow> </math>","<math><mrow>  <mtext>IV</mtext>  <mo>&gt;</mo>  <mtext>III</mtext>  <mo>&gt;</mo>  <mtext>I</mtext>  <mo>&gt;</mo>  <mtext>II</mtext></mrow></math>","<math> <mrow> <mtext>II</mtext> <mo>&gt;</mo> <mtext>IV</mtext> <mo>&gt;</mo> <mtext>I</mtext> <mo>&gt;</mo> <mtext>III</mtext> </mrow> </math>","<math><mrow>  <mtext>I</mtext>  <mo>&gt;</mo>  <mtext>II</mtext>  <mo>&gt;</mo>  <mtext>III</mtext>  <mo>&gt;</mo>  <mtext>IV</mtext></mrow></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"Acidity is directly proportional to conjugated base stability.<br /><img alt=\"\" height=\"182\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EM0010392_AnsExp1_2.jpg\" width=\"444\" /><br /><img alt=\"\" height=\"172\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EM0010392_AnsExp1_1.jpg\" width=\"469\" /><br /><br />Stability order of conjugate bases is III &gt; I &gt; II &gt; IV<br /><br />Conjugate base in I is stabilised by - I &gt; + M<br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 12.7272720336914px; line-height: 20.8000011444092px;\">Conjugate&nbsp;</span>base in II is destabilised by + I and hyperconjugation.<br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 12.7272720336914px; line-height: 20.8000011444092px;\">Conjugate</span><span style=\"font-size: 12.7272720336914px; line-height: 20.8000011444092px;\">&nbsp;</span> base in III is stabilised by strong withdrawing effect of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> by - I &amp; - M effect.<br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 12.7272720336914px; line-height: 20.8000011444092px;\">Conjugate&nbsp;</span>base in IV is destabilised by + M effect of<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>OCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"left\"><mtr><mtd><mi>acidic</mi><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi>character</mi><mtext>&#8201;&#8201;</mtext><mo>&#8733;</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mtext>&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;&#8201;</mtext><mo>&#8733;</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi>HC</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow></mfrac></mtd></mtr></mtable></math><br /><br />Electron releasing group (i.e +I effect, +M) decreases the acidic strength&nbsp;<br />Electron withdrawing group (i.e -I effect,-M) increases acidic strength.<br /><br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5386402e-e2b5-4ca8-b3d2-85df6bf58969-38.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 160px;\" /><br />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":29657,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false"],"answer":1,"solution":"Statement I: In the tert-butyl carbocation $(CH_3)_3C^+$, there are three methyl groups attached to the carbocationic carbon. Each methyl group has 3 $\\alpha$-hydrogens, making a total of 9 $\\alpha$-hydrogens. Thus, 9 hyperconjugation interactions are possible, which significantly stabilize the carbocation. Statement I is true.<br>Statement II: In the methyl carbocation $CH_3^+$, there are no $\\alpha$-carbons and consequently no $\\alpha$-hydrogens. Hyperconjugation requires the presence of at least one $\\alpha$-hydrogen on a carbon adjacent to the $sp^2$ hybridized carbocation center. Therefore, zero hyperconjugation interactions are possible in $CH_3^+$. Statement II is false because it claims three hyperconjugation interactions are possible.<br>Conclusion: Statement I is true but Statement II is false.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29774,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cyclohex</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>en</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>ol</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>Hydroxyhex</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>ene</mi><mo> </mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cyclohex</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>en</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>ol</mi><mo> </mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cyclohex</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>en</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>ol</mi><mo> </mo></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The structure of the IUPAC compound is</p><p>Secondary prefix+ primary prefix + root word + Primary suffix + Secondary suffix</p><p>It is a cyclic compound, with one <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OH</mi></math> group on position <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> and double bond at position <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ffec23be-84f4-4cf4-826c-c02e7391f3f1.png\" style=\"width: 196px; height: 222px;\"/></p><p>There is no secondary prefix in the above compound. primary prefix is cyclo. Root word is hex, primary suffix is en and secondary suffix is ol.</p><p>Hence, the name is Cyclohex-2-en-1-ol.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29751,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>CN</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>NHR</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>OCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>COOH</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>COOR</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>CHO</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>COR</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>CN</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>CHO</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NHCOCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>COOR</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Due to the presence of some groups, the electron density decreases on ortho and para positions. So, the electron density on meta position is relatively higher than ortho and para positions. Thus, these groups directs the electrophilic substitution on meta position.</p><p>Due to the presence of some groups, the electron density decreases on ortho and para positions. So, the electron density on meta position is relatively higher than ortho and para positions. Thus, these groups directs the electrophilic substitution on meta position. If the atom of group which is attached to benzene ring has pi bond then that group act as meta directing group.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ddccc615-3711-4dc2-a812-ff6d7ad4a69c.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 174px;\"/></p><p>All are <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>–</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>,</mo></math> Hence meta directing groups.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29731,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"For 3d transition series; Oxidising power : $\\mathrm{V}^{+5} < \\mathrm{Cr}^{+6} < \\mathrm{Mn}^{+7}$\n$\\mathrm{V}^{+5}:[\\mathrm{Ar}] 4 \\mathrm{~s}^0 3 \\mathrm{~d}^0$\nNumber of unpaired electron $=0$\n$\\mu=0$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29937,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#60;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Acidity <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi></math> stability of conjugate base</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d550caea-0699-4020-aaa6-9e07de2b97e2-image.png\" style=\"width: 624px; height: 87px;\" /></p><p>(Stability of conjugate bases)</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29805,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>3-chloro-1-butene undergo protonation and gives secondary carbocation according Markonikov&#39;s addition in the first step. In the second step the lone pair on the chlorine attacks the positively charged carbon to form cyclic intermediate. Now the nucleophile in the reaction i.e., chloride ion attacks cyclic intermediate and forms two structural products as shown below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/48fec7d5-df60-4c2a-9e7f-0c7c62501753.png\" style=\"width: 321px; height: 190px;\" /></p><p>2,2-dichlorobutane exit in single isomer only, but 2,3-dichlorobutane exhibits three isomers.&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29707,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["(A) and (E) Only","(A), (D) and (E) Only","(B) and (C) Only","(C), (D) and (E) Only"],"answer":1,"solution":"(A) $\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}=\\mathrm{CH}_2$. GI is not possible\n(B) Trans isomer has identical atoms/groups on the opposite side of double bond.\n\n\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Db5AisIl9cewjlEPUyYOfwRVhpsEEZ8zskkB2q44Rv0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 1)","image":null}]